{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"50c8f3c1-854d-4440-98ef-262b2dfccf0e","content":"The repository is empty, so there's no project-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance based on .NET and macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS writes to `/cores` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** macOS will write a file like `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **If `/cores` is empty**, macOS may have Crash Reporter enabled instead. Check:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n5. **Analyze the core dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily adjust SIP settings or use `lldb` to attach live:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   run\n   # after crash, use `bt` for backtrace\n   ```\n\n**Key notes for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, `createdump` (a CoreCLR tool) isn't bundled. The macOS-native core dump + `lldb` workflow is the standard fallback. You can also install `dotnet-dump` but it has limited NativeAOT support — `lldb` is preferred.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4a20df4-5eca-4687-8664-0caf4721a358","outputTokens":403,"requestId":"D7C8:11B452:1061CDD:12B8F92:69F2B5A6"},"id":"d2bf65cf-7448-4bee-ae0a-b3a0a857ff28","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:51:46.984Z","parentId":"5f14b2e6-c59a-475d-b955-95445b85f1a5"}
